OL,24,ANext PageBS-SE Eng NewsCThis DayFReg TV
FL,415,410,120,260,000,100
PN,41402
SC,0002
CT,2,C
PS,c008
OL,0,        ECIMSBWebfax 1   F414A1774102278
OL,3,CKing Harold's forced march to Battle
OL,4,Cof Hastings 'implausible'
OL,6,FThe AngloSaxon Chronicle, one of the
OL,7,Fearliest and most complete written
OL,8,Frecords of English history, seems to
OL,9,Fimply that Harold had dismissed his
OL,10,Ffleet, leaving him no choice but to
OL,11,Frush his troops south on foot.
OL,13,FBut Prof Licence suggests a record
OL,14,Fthat the ships "came home" was
OL,15,Fmistakenly interpreted by Victorian
OL,16,Fhistorians as meaning Harold disbanded
OL,17,Fthe navy.
OL,26,@vD@POUvD@ZO]
OL,1,W~s1x0~s1~s hw1~k4~c1 hw}h7}j7}   G2/9
OL,2,W,.!" ,.!+, "-$/*%+.!+,*%/*%/*-'T(,,,,,,
OL,23,TppppppppppppppppppGsource: itv.com/news
OL,24,ANext PageBS-SE Eng NewsCThis DayFReg TV
FL,415,410,120,260,000,100
PN,41403
SC,0003
CT,2,C
PS,c008
OL,0,        ECIMSBWebfax 1   F414A1774102278
OL,3,CKing Harold's forced march to Battle
OL,4,Cof Hastings 'implausible'
OL,6,FThey actually returned to their home
OL,7,Fbase of London and remained
OL,8,Foperational throughout the year, he
OL,9,Fargues.
OL,11,F"Harold's weary, unmounted men
OL,12,Fcovering nearly 200 miles in 10 days
OL,13,Fand then continuing straight to the
OL,14,FHastings peninsula is implausible
OL,15,Fgiven medieval roads and the aftermath
OL,16,Fof battle," said Prof Licence.
OL,18,F"Only a mad general would have sent
OL,19,Fall his men on foot in this way if
OL,20,Fship transports were available."
OL,26,@sD@AOUxD@KO]zD@AOU|D@`O]
OL,1,W~s1x0~s1~s hw1~k4~c1 hw}h7}j7}   G3/9
OL,2,W,.!" ,.!+, "-$/*%+.!+,*%/*%/*-'T(,,,,,,
OL,23,TppppppppppppppppppGsource: itv.com/news
OL,24,ANext PageBS-SE Eng NewsCThis DayFReg TV
FL,415,410,120,260,000,100
PN,41404
SC,0004
CT,2,C
PS,c008
OL,0,        ECIMSBWebfax 1   F414A1774102278
OL,3,CKing Harold's forced march to Battle
OL,4,Cof Hastings 'implausible'
OL,6,FHe said that he noticed "multiple
OL,7,Fcontemporary writers referring to
OL,8,FHarold's fleet, while modern
OL,9,Fhistorians were dismissing those
OL,10,Freferences or trying to explain them
OL,11,Faway".
OL,13,F"I checked the evidence for him having
OL,14,Fsent the fleet home and found that it
OL,15,Fwas just a misunderstanding," Prof
OL,16,FLicence said.
OL,18,F"I went looking in the sources for
OL,19,Fevidence of a forced march and found
OL,20,Fthere wasn't any.
OL,26,@nD@YOUsD@EO]uD@AOUwD@]O]zD@AOU
OL,1,W~s1x0~s1~s hw1~k4~c1 hw}h7}j7}   G4/9
OL,2,W,.!" ,.!+, "-$/*%+.!+,*%/*%/*-'T(,,,,,,
OL,23,TppppppppppppppppppGsource: itv.com/news
OL,24,ANext PageBS-SE Eng NewsCThis DayFReg TV
FL,415,410,120,260,000,100
PN,41405
SC,0005
CT,2,C
PS,c008
OL,0,        ECIMSBWebfax 1   F414A1774102278
OL,3,CKing Harold's forced march to Battle
OL,4,Cof Hastings 'implausible'
OL,6,F"Harold's campaign was not a desperate
OL,7,Fdash across England, it was a
OL,8,Fsophisticated landsea operation.
OL,10,F"The idea of a heroic march is a
OL,11,FVictorian invention that has shaped
OL,12,Four understanding, or
OL,13,Fmisunderstanding, of 1066 for far too
OL,14,Flong."
OL,16,FContemporary sources describe Harold
OL,17,Fsending hundreds of ships to block
OL,18,FDuke William of Normandy ` also known
OL,19,Fas William the Conqueror ` after the
OL,20,FNorman landing.
OL,26,@nD@AOUrD@AOUvD@FO]
OL,1,W~s1x0~s1~s hw1~k4~c1 hw}h7}j7}   G5/9
OL,2,W,.!" ,.!+, "-$/*%+.!+,*%/*%/*-'T(,,,,,,
OL,23,TppppppppppppppppppGsource: itv.com/news
OL,24,ANext PageBS-SE Eng NewsCThis DayFReg TV
FL,415,410,120,260,000,100
PN,41406
SC,0006
CT,2,C
PS,c008
OL,0,        ECIMSBWebfax 1   F414A1774102278
OL,3,CKing Harold's forced march to Battle
OL,4,Cof Hastings 'implausible'
OL,6,FProf Licence said the fleet was used
OL,7,Fto defend the south coast, then to
OL,8,Fsupport Harold's campaign against the
OL,9,FViking invasion led by Harald
OL,10,FHardrada, then to head back south to
OL,11,Fface the Norman invasion.
OL,13,FProf Licence said the research
OL,14,F"reframes the events of 1066 and
OL,15,Fhighlights a previously overlooked
OL,16,Faspect of AngloSaxon maritime
OL,17,Fcapability".
OL,26,@vD@AOUyD@KO]
OL,1,W~s1x0~s1~s hw1~k4~c1 hw}h7}j7}   G6/9
OL,2,W,.!" ,.!+, "-$/*%+.!+,*%/*%/*-'T(,,,,,,
OL,23,TppppppppppppppppppGsource: itv.com/news
OL,24,ANext PageBS-SE Eng NewsCThis DayFReg TV
FL,415,410,120,260,000,100
PN,41407
SC,0007
CT,2,C
PS,c008
OL,0,        ECIMSBWebfax 1   F414A1774102278
OL,3,CKing Harold's forced march to Battle
OL,4,Cof Hastings 'implausible'
OL,6,F"Harold was not a reactive, exhausted
OL,7,Fcommander, he was a strategist using
OL,8,FEngland's naval assets to wage a co-
OL,9,Fordinated defence," he said.
OL,11,FHarold's death in the Battle of
OL,12,FHastings is depicted in the Bayeux
OL,13,FTapestry, which shows him clutching an
OL,14,Farrow to his eye.
OL,16,FThe victorious William became the
OL,17,Ffirst Norman king of England.
OL,26,@nD@AOUqD@SO]
OL,1,W~s1x0~s1~s hw1~k4~c1 hw}h7}j7}   G7/9
OL,2,W,.!" ,.!+, "-$/*%+.!+,*%/*%/*-'T(,,,,,,
OL,23,TppppppppppppppppppGsource: itv.com/news
OL,24,ANext PageBS-SE Eng NewsCThis DayFReg TV
FL,415,410,120,260,000,100
PN,41408
SC,0008
CT,2,C
PS,c008
OL,0,        ECIMSBWebfax 1   F414A1774102278
OL,3,CKing Harold's forced march to Battle
OL,4,Cof Hastings 'implausible'
OL,6,FProfessor Michael Lewis, curator of
OL,7,Fthe Bayeux Tapestry Exhibition at the
OL,8,FBritish Museum, said: "With the Bayeux
OL,9,FTapestry coming to the British Museum
OL,10,Flater this year, Prof Tom Licence's
OL,11,Fresearch shows there is much still to
OL,12,Fbe learned about the events of 1066.
OL,14,F"It is clearly a fascinating discovery
OL,15,Fthat following the Battle of Stamford
OL,16,FBridge Harold took an easier, more
OL,17,Flogical, trip south by ship to meet
OL,18,FDuke William in battle, rather than a
OL,19,Flong trek overland, as has long been
OL,20,Fsupposed.
OL,26,@pD@WOUvD@AOU
OL,1,W~s1x0~s1~s hw1~k4~c1 hw}h7}j7}   G8/9
OL,2,W,.!" ,.!+, "-$/*%+.!+,*%/*%/*-'T(,,,,,,
OL,23,TppppppppppppppppppGsource: itv.com/news
OL,24,ANext PageBS-SE Eng NewsCThis DayFReg TV
FL,415,410,120,260,000,100
PN,41409
SC,0009
CT,2,C
PS,c008
OL,0,        ECIMSBWebfax 1   F414A1774102278
OL,3,CKing Harold's forced march to Battle
OL,4,Cof Hastings 'implausible'
OL,6,F"Hopefully this new research inspires
OL,7,Fpeople to also come and see the
OL,8,Ftapestry whilst it is in London."
OL,10,FProf Licence is to present his
OL,11,Fresearch at The Maritime and Political
OL,12,FWorld of 1066 conference at Oxford
OL,13,FUniversity on March 24.
OL,15,FReporting History sees journalists
OL,16,Fjoin News At Ten anchor Tom Bradby to
OL,17,Frevisit their remarkable on-the-day
OL,18,Freports of the defining events of the
OL,19,Fmodern age. Listen to the episodes
OL,20,Fbelow...
OL,26,@nD@AOUpD@aO]
